You can allow the database to do the heaving lifting here. You can query the database using [`GROUP BY`](https://laravel.com/api/6.x/Illuminate/Database/Query/Builder.html#method_groupBy), then remove everything that doesn&#39;t match your query.

```php
$ids = Model::groupBy([&#39;relation_id&#39;, &#39;foo&#39;, &#39;bar&#39;, &#39;timestamp&#39;])
            -&gt;get([&#39;id&#39;])
            -&gt;all();
```
This translates to the following SQL:

```sql
SELECT id FROM models GROUP BY relation_id, foo, bar, timestamp;
```

So now `$ids` is an array of IDs where the other columns are unique (`[1, 4]`). So you can execute the following to remove all other rows from the DB:

```php
Model::whereNotIn(&#39;id&#39;, $ids)-&gt;delete();
```

However, since `$ids` is probably ***huge***, you are likely to hit some upper limit constraints. In that case, you can try using [`array_chunk()`](https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-chunk.php) to add multiple `whereNotIn` clauses to the query:

```php
$query = Model::query();

foreach(array_chunk($ids, 500) as $chunk) {
  $query-&gt;whereNotIn(&#39;id&#39;, $chunk);
}

$query-&gt;delete();
```

I created an [SQL Fiddle](http://sqlfiddle.com/#!9/7743dd/6) where you can test this out.

